Solution. The middle term of an arithmetic sequence is the arithmetic mean of its neighbors, i.e.,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& 2 \cdot \log _{2 b} 2 a=\log _{b} a+\log _{4 b} 4 a \\
& 2 \cdot \frac{\log _{2} 2 a}{\log _{2} 2 b}=\frac{\log _{2} a}{\log _{2} b}+\frac{\log _{2} 4 a}{\log _{2} 4 b} \\
& 2 \cdot \frac{1+\log _{2} a}{1+\log _{2} b}=\frac{\log _{2} a}{\log _{2} b}+\frac{2+\log _{2} a}{2+\log _{2} b}
\end{aligned}
$$

By substituting $x=\log _{2} a$ and $y=\log _{2} b$ and multiplying by the common denominator, we will get $x=y$, hence $a=b$.

The answer is $\boxed{b}$.

